# Conventional Commit Style

Follow the [Conventional Commits 1.0.0](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/) format for every git commit message.

## Required format

`<type>[optional scope]: <description>`

Optional body and footers may be added after a blank line.

## Allowed types

- `feat`: new feature
- `fix`: bug fix
- `docs`: documentation only
- `style`: formatting only (no behavior changes)
- `refactor`: code change without behavior change
- `perf`: performance improvement
- `test`: tests added/updated
- `build`: build/dependency changes
- `ci`: CI/CD workflow changes
- `chore`: maintenance tasks
- `revert`: revert a previous commit

## Rules

- Use lowercase type and scope.
- Keep description short, imperative, and specific.
- Do not end the subject line with a period.
- Include `BREAKING CHANGE: ...` footer when applicable (or use `!` before `:`).

## Examples

- `feat(ci): build thesis and presentation via matrix`
- `fix(bib): remove duplicate souza citation key`
- `docs(readme): clarify latex build prerequisites`
